<subSubSection box="[199,1065,880,903]" pageId="3" pageNumber="587" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,151,972]" box="[199,1065,880,903]" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,327,880,903]" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet refers to the black markings on head and thorax.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="587" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,151,972]" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,309,914,937]" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">Remarks.</emphasis>
Numerous dark brown to black markings on the head and thorax, the pair of lamellate processes on the aedeagal shaft and a narrow ventral process on the pygofer distinguish this species from other species of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Baker" baseAuthorityYear="1915" box="[1269,1376,949,972]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="587" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Idiocerini">Idiocerini</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
